{
  "answer": "**Bṛhaspati Smṛti**\n\nIn the *Bṛhaspati Smṛti*, *lekhya* (\"document\" or \"writing\") is introduced as one of the three primary kinds of human proof (*puruṣapramāṇa*) in *vyavahāra* (legal procedure or litigation), alongside witnesses (* sākṣin*) and possession/inference (*bhoga/hetu*).[^1] The operative claim is that a valid document—properly detailing elements like place, time, parties, witnesses, scribe, and transaction type (*e.g.*, partition, gift, sale, pledge)—establishes proof independently and comprehensively.[^2] Documents are classified into royal, place-specific, and self-written types, further subdivided into seven worldly kinds (*e.g.*, partition deed, gift deed) and three royal charters.[^3]\n\n**Charles Comte, *Traité de Législation***\n\nNo passages in the available *Traité de Législation* (Vols. I–IV) treat writing/documents (*écrit*, *document*) explicitly as evidence (*preuve*) or compare it to oral testimony (*témoignage oral*). Searches across English translations for relevant terms (evidence, testimony, witness, document, writing, *preuve*, *témoignage*, *témoins*, *écrit*) yielded no matches on evidentiary use. The work focuses on analytical method, moral/philosophical systems of legislation, human development, slavery, and social organization, without addressing legal proof standards. If such treatment exists, it is not in the translated corpus.\n\n**Comparative Reliability**\n\nNeither tradition explicitly ranks writing/documents as more or less reliable than oral testimony/witnesses (*sākṣin*). In *Bṛhaspati*, both are coordinate \"human proofs,\" with witnesses requiring extensive validation (e.g., number, qualities, faults like greed or contradiction), while a valid document suffices alone, excluding ordeals or witnesses.[^4] Oral testimony dominates where no document exists, but is subordinate when one does. No such comparison appears for Comte.\n\n[^1]: *Bṛhaspati Smṛti*, Ch. 1, [¶ Brh_1,4.7](/works/unknown-brhaspati-smrti-0fd070/01/translation/#p-c9cb41).\n[^2]: *Bṛhaspati Smṛti*, Ch. 1, [¶ Brh_1,6.1–6.49](/works/unknown-brhaspati-smrti-0fd070/01/translation/#p-bbce9d).\n[^3]: *Bṛhaspati Smṛti*, Ch. 1, [¶ Brh_1,6.3–6.28](/works/unknown-brhaspati-smrti-0fd070/01/translation/#p-400669).\n[^4]: *Bṛhaspati Smṛti*, Ch. 1, [¶ Brh_1,4.12](/works/unknown-brhaspati-smrti-0fd070/01/translation/#p-44a57a).",
